ce:section.ce:para:
The solid sample of CNP/TiO2 was analyzed by X-ray diffraction (XRD), from which the diffraction pattern (Fig. 3
                     , Table 1
                     ) is consistent with the anatase phase for the nanoscale TiO2. The sample of CNPs before the TiO2 capping is amorphous. The growth of crystalline anatase TiO2 in the conversion from Ti(OEt)4 might have benefited from the hydrothermal annealing [32–34]. The XRD pattern exhibits significant peak broadening, consistent with the nanoscale nature of the TiO2 coating. According to the Scherrer equation [35], the peak broadening corresponds to about 5 nm in the average size of the nanoscale TiO2 (Table 1), though in this case the TiO2 is unlikely in the form of well-defined nanoparticles, namely that for the nanoscale TiO2 coating individual CNPs the applicability of the Scherrer equation may be somewhat limited. Relevant to such an argument is the composition of carbon and TiO2 in the CNP/TiO2 sample estimated by using thermal gravimetric analysis (TGA).
